        {
            "id": "a9898a38b9454a198f907",
            "questionText": "A seesaw, which is a uniform plank of length $!$L = 4\\,\\text{m}$!$ and mass $!$M = 10\\,\\text{kg}$!$, is pivoted at its center. A child with a mass $!$m_1 = 30\\,\\text{kg}$!$ sits at one end of the plank. Another child, with a mass $!$m_2 = 20\\,\\text{kg}$!$, sits $!$1\\,\\text{m}$!$ from the opposite end. If the seesaw is released from rest, calculate the initial angular acceleration of the seesaw about the pivot point.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "7517ce77db094f25b0bd9",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the appropriate formula that relates a force acting at a distance from the pivot to the resulting torque. Please select the correct formula.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "66c394e5-9b27-4235-9105-6b2e0ba0b2b0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = F d$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = F/d$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = d/F$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "145ddb289b51436e80cb3",
                    "stepText": "Using the concept of torque, compute the net torque about the pivot. Consider that the lever arm for the child seated at the end is half the seesaw's length and for the other child, the lever arm is the difference between the half-length and the given distance from that end. Now, calculate the net torque (remember to use the gravitational acceleration $!$g = 9.8\\,\\text{m/s}^2$!$).",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "392"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "N\u00b7m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "66c394e5-9b27-4235-9105-6b2e0ba0b2b0"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "bdead82360fd4dd98d894",
                    "stepText": "Next, we need the formula for the moment of inertia of a uniform rod about its center. Please choose the correct formula.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e7c0b9dd-4995-4142-ba78-a54339d150c3"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{12} M L^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{3} M L^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = M L^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "b50578f4313a455ba73f6",
                    "stepText": "Now, compute the total moment of inertia of the system. This includes the moment of inertia of the rod and the contributions from each child treated as a point mass (using $!$I = m d^2$!$ for point masses). Calculate the total moment of inertia using the given values.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "153.33"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg\u00b7m^2",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "b5685466-7a37-4ece-ab26-a0e7c37357f4",
                        "e7c0b9dd-4995-4142-ba78-a54339d150c3"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "4e65fbc8656448d9ada06",
                    "stepText": "Next, identify the correct formula that relates the net torque, the total moment of inertia, and the angular acceleration. Please select the correct relation.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "3b2a38ec-ad3c-4fda-9fed-c1f652dea80e"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau_{net} = I \\alpha$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau_{net} = I / \\alpha$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\alpha = I \\tau_{net}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "a3d5f554aed845e7bcb20",
                    "stepText": "Finally, using the net torque and the total moment of inertia you've calculated, determine the angular acceleration of the seesaw. Compute the value of angular acceleration.",
                    "stepText2": "",
